1. Availability: Seller makes electric energy, capacity and ancillary services available under this Tariff to any purchaser, except as prohibited below.
2. Applicability: This Tariff is applicable to all wholesale sales of energy, capacity, and ancillary services by Seller, which are (a) subject to the jurisdiction of the Commission, and (b) not made pursuant to another tariff on file with the Commission.
3. Rates: All sales shall be made at rates established by agreement between the purchaser and Seller.
4. Other Terms and Conditions: All other terms and conditions shall be established by agreement between the purchaser and Seller.
5. Seller Category: Seller is a Category 2 seller, as defined in 18 C.F.R. § 35.36(a), in the Southwest region. Seller is a Category 1 seller, as defined in 18 C.F.R. § 35.36(a), in each of the Northeast, Northwest, Southwest Power Pool, Central, and Southeast regions.
6. Compliance with Commission Regulations: Seller shall comply with the provisions of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subpart H, as applicable, and with any conditions the Commission imposes in its orders concerning Sellers market-based rate authority, including orders in which the Commission authorizes Seller to engage in affiliate sales under this Tariff or otherwise restricts or limits Sellers market-based rate authority. Failure to comply with the applicable provisions of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subpart H, and with any orders of the Commission concerning Sellers market-based rate authority, will constitute a violation of this Tariff.
7. Limitations and Exemptions Regarding Market-Based Rate Authority: Seller has received waiver of: Subparts B and C of Part 35, except for sections 35.12(a), 35.13(b), 35.15 and 35.16; Part 41, Part 101, with the exception that waiver of the provisions of Part 101 that apply to hydropower licensees has not been granted with respect to licensed hydropower projects, and Part 141, except section 141.15; and received blanket approval under Part 34. RE Papago LLC, Docket No. ER24- -000 (2024).
8. Ancillary Services: Seller may make available to any purchaser the following ancillary services:
PJM: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, energy imbalance service, and operating reserve service (which includes spinning, 10-minute, and 30-minute reserves) for sale into the market administered by PJM Interconnection, L.L.C. (PJM) and, where the PJM Open Access Transmission Tariff permits, the self-supply of these services to purchasers for a bilateral sale that is used to satisfy the ancillary services requirements of the PJM Office of Interconnection.
New York: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute non-synchronous, 30-minute operating reserves, 10-minute spinning reserves, and 10-minute non-spinning reserves) for sale to purchasers in the market administered by the New York Independent System Operator, Inc.
New England: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service (automatic generator control), operating reserve service (which includes 10-minute spinning reserve, 10-minute non-spinning reserve, and 30-minute operating reserve service) to purchasers within the markets administered by the ISO New England, Inc.
California: Seller offers regulation service, spinning reserve service, and non-spinning reserve service to the California Independent System Operator Corporation (CAISO) and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to the CAISO.
MISO: Seller offers regulation service and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute spinning reserve and 10-minute supplemental reserve) for sale to the Midcontinent Independent System Operator, Inc. (MISO) and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to MISO.
Southwest Power Pool: Seller offers regulation service and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute spinning reserve and 10-minute supplemental reserve) for sale to the Southwest Power Pool, Inc. (SPP) and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to SPP.
Third-party ancillary services: Seller offers Regulation Service, Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service, Energy and Generator Imbalance Service, Operating Reserve-Spinning, Operating Reserve Supplemental, and Primary Frequency Response Service. Sales will not include the following: (1) sales to an RTO or an ISO, i.e., where that entity has no ability to self-supply ancillary services but instead depends on third parties; and (2) sales to a traditional, franchised public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier, or sales where the underlying transmission service is on the system of the public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier. Sales of Operating Reserve-Spinning and Operating Reserve-Supplemental will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except where the Commission has granted authorization. Sales of Regulation Service and Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except at rates not to exceed the buying public utility transmission providers OATT rate for the same service or where the Commission has granted authorization.
9. Effective Date: This Tariff is effective on such date as set by the Commission.

SHARED FACILITIES AGREEMENT
THIS SHARED FACILITIES AGREEMENT (this Agreement) is made as of May 6, 2024 (the Agreement Date), by and between RE PAPAGO LLC, a Delaware limited liability company, in its individual capacity (Papago BESS) and in its capacity as Manager hereunder, and RE PAPAGO PV LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (Papago PV). Papago BESS and Papago PV are collectively referred to herein as the Project Companies and each individually as a Project Company. The Project Companies, together with the Manager, are collectively referred to herein as the Parties and individually as a Party. The terms Project Company and Party shall include the permitted successors and permitted assignees of such Person. Certain capitalized terms used in this Agreement are given defined in Appendix A attached hereto.
RECITALS
A. Papago BESS holds or anticipates holding certain real property option, leasehold, rights-of-way and/or fee interests in all or a portion of that certain land located in Maricopa County, Arizona described on Exhibit A-1 as generally shown on Exhibit A-2 (the Papago BESS Property). Papago BESS intends to develop a 300 MWAC/ 1200 MWhAC battery energy storage project on the Papago BESS Property (the Papago BESS Project).
B. Papago PV holds or anticipates holding certain real property option, leasehold, rights-of-way and/or fee interests in all or a portion of that certain land located in Maricopa County, Arizona described on Exhibit A-3 as generally shown on Exhibit A-4 (the Papago PV Property). Papago PV intends to develop a 150 MWAC / 192 MWDC solar energy generation project on the Papago PV Property (the Papago PV Project).
C. Papago BESS is a party to that certain Large Generator Interconnection Agreement with Arizona Public Service Company (APS) and Central Arizona Water Conservation District (CAWCD), which agreement Papago BESS intends to amend to add Papago PV as a party and make certain related changes (as amended, the Interconnection Agreement), and which relates to the interconnection of the Papago BESS Project and Papago PV Project to the APS controlled transmission system with a Point of Interconnection at APSs 500 kV Delaney Substation. Manager, Papago BESS, and Papago PV intend to enter into a co-tenancy agreement, with Manager acting as Manager thereunder, relating to the sharing of rights and responsibilities under the Interconnection Agreement (the Co-Tenancy Agreement).
D. The Papago BESS Project and the Papago PV Project are individually referred to herein as a Project, and collectively as the Projects. The Papago BESS Property and the Papago PV Property are collectively referred to as the Properties and the portion of the Properties upon which a Project sits is referred to as a Property.
E. The Project Companies hold or anticipate holding, as tenants in common, undivided interests in certain real property options, franchise, leasehold, easement and co-tenancy rights, rights-of-way, encroachment rights, crossing rights, rights under non-disturbance agreements, rights under waivers, rights under consents and/or fee interests described in Exhibit B-1 (the Shared Premises Property Rights) relating to the property described in Exhibit B-2 (such premises subject to the Shared Premises Property Rights, the Shared Premises).

F. The Project Companies hold certain permits relating to the Shared Premises and the Properties and which are described in Exhibit B-3 (the Shared Permits).
G. The Project Companies wish to share the use and cost of certain electrical transmission, communications and other structures and facilities and associated real property rights, and to engage Manager to construct, operate, maintain, repair and manage the foregoing, all in accordance with and subject to the terms and conditions of this Agreement.
NOW, THEREFORE, in consideration of the mutual promises contained herein, and for other good and valuable consideration, the receipt and sufficiency of which are hereby acknowledged by the Parties, the Parties agree as follows:
ARTICLE 1
DEFINITIONS AND INTERPRETATIONS
1.1 Definitions. As used in this Agreement, including the Recitals, and except as required by grammatical usage and apart from proper nouns, each capitalized term has the meaning given to it in this Agreement and in the Schedule of Definitions attached as Appendix A.
1.2 Interpretation. In this Agreement, unless a clear, contrary intention appears: (a) the singular includes the plural and vice versa; (b) reference to any Person includes such Persons successors and assigns but, in the case of a Project Company, only if such assigns are permitted by this Agreement, and reference to a Person in a particular capacity excludes such Person in any other capacity; (c) reference to any gender includes each other gender; (d) reference to any agreement (including this Agreement), document or instrument means such agreement, document or instrument as amended or modified and in effect from time to time in accordance with the terms thereof and, if applicable, the terms of this Agreement; (e) reference to any Governmental Requirement means such Governmental Requirement as amended, modified, codified, or reenacted, in whole or in part, and in effect from time to time, including, if applicable, rules and regulations promulgated thereunder; (f) reference to any Section means such Section of this Agreement, and references in any Section or definition to any clause means such clause of such Section or definition; (g) hereunder, hereof, hereto and words of similar import shall be deemed references to this Agreement as a whole and not to any particular Section or other provision of this Agreement; (h) including means including without limiting the generality of any description such term; and (i) relative to the determination of any period of time, from means from and including, to means to but excluding and through means through and including.
ARTICLE 2
SHARED PREMISES
2.1 Declaration of Intention. The Project Companies hereby declare that their relationship in and to the Shared Premises Property Rights and the Shared Facilities is and will be that of tenants in common, and that each Project Company will have an undivided interest in the Shared Premises and the Shared Facilities on and subject to the terms, conditions, limitations and

requirements set forth in this Agreement. The arrangements and ownership structure contemplated by this Agreement are not being made with the intention or expectation of producing revenue or making or sharing in any profits from the ownership or operation of the Shared Premises or the Shared Facilities, but are instead intended as a form of legal ownership whereby the Project Companies can accomplish their respective objectives of independently owning and operating their respective undivided interests in, and sharing the use of, the Shared Premises and the Shared Facilities in connection with their respective Projects and businesses and to enable the Project Companies to perform and discharge certain of their obligations under the Interconnection Agreement, the Co-Tenancy Agreement, and their respective Revenue Agreements.
2.2 Shared Premises Property Rights.
(a) The Shared Premises Property Rights are described on Exhibits B-1 in the locations described and depicted on Exhibit B-2. The Shared Premises Property Rights allow or will allow for the development, design, construction, Operation and Maintenance of the Shared Facilities.
(b) Each Project Company shall own and hold an interest in the Shared Premises Property Rights, jointly, as tenants-in-common, in equal shares with respect to and for the joint use of the Shared Facilities as provided herein. Without limiting the generality of the foregoing, the foregoing individual interest shall include (i) the joint exercise of the Shared Premises Property Rights on, over, under, across and through the Shared Premises, and (ii) the joint use of those certain Shared Facilities located on or under the Shared Premises (whether now existing or hereafter constructed). Each Project Company hereby consents to the use of the Shared Premises Property Rights by the Project Companies and Manager pursuant to this Agreement, including without limitation, where such Shared Premises Property Rights affect, or otherwise touch and concern, other real property interests or estates held by such Project Company so long as such use is consistent with the requirements of this Agreement and the rights of the Parties hereunder. To the extent that any Shared Premises or Shared Premises Property Rights are not held specifically by the Project Companies in accordance with their Proportionate Shares, the Parties shall nonetheless share rights and obligations with respect to such Shared Premises and Shared Premises Property Rights in accordance with their Proportionate Shares.
(c) Papago BESS has the right use an access road (the Shared Access Road) pursuant to that certain Access Easement set forth in that Land Lease for Energy Storage Facilities and Related Rights as disclosed by that certain Memorandum of Lease recorded December 26, 2023 in the Official Records of Maricopa County, as Document Number 20230654192, as amended by that certain First Amendment to Land Lease and to Memorandum of Land Lease recorded February 27, 2024 in the Official Records of Maricopa County, as Document Number 20240097743, and as further amended by that certain Second Amendment to Land Lease and to Memorandum of Land Lease recorded May 6, 2024 in the Official Records of Maricopa County, as Document Number 20240240219 (the BESS Access Easement). Papago PV also has the right to use the Shared Access Road pursuant to that certain Grant of Access Road Easement by and between RE Papago LandCo LLC, as Grantor, and Papago PV, as Grantee, dated March 20, 2024 and recorded in the Official Records of Maricopa County, Arizona as Document Number 20240145978 (the PV Access Easement). The rights and obligations of Papago BESS and Papago PV to use the Shared Access Road shall be governed by the terms of this Agreement

until the earlier of (i) the termination of either the BESS Access Easement or the PV Access Easement, as evidenced by a recorded termination of the applicable easement, or (ii) Papago BESS and Papago PVs execution of a road maintenance agreement, shared roadway agreement or other agreement to separately set forth their rights and obligations with respect to the Shared Access Road.
2.3 Shared Facilities.
(a) The Project Companies plan to procure, install and construct, or have procured, installed and constructed, certain facilities for electrical transmission, interconnection, communications and other structures and facilities, as described on Exhibit C-1 (the Shared Facilities), which may be altered or reconstructed in accordance with this Agreement, for shared use by the Project Companies (collectively, the Shared Facilities). A depiction of the Shared Facilities is set forth on Exhibit C-2.
(b) Each Project Company shall own and hold an undivided interest in the Shared Facilities, jointly with the other Project Company, as tenants in common in proportion to its Proportionate Share as set forth on Exhibit D for the benefit, operation and use of its Project as provided herein.
2.4 Access to the Shared Premises and Shared Facilities.
(a) By Project Companies. Subject to the conditions and additional rights described below, each Project Company and any Secured Party of such Project Company shall have access to and the right to enter onto the Shared Premises and the Shared Facilities to the extent reasonably necessary for (i) inspection of the Shared Premises on which the Shared Facilities are situated and the Shared Facilities located thereon, without unduly interfering with the normal operations of the other Project Company or the Manager and otherwise subject to the terms and conditions set forth in this Agreement, (ii) construction or Operation and Maintenance of the Shared Facilities in the event the Manager fails to do so, in accordance with the terms hereof, or (iii) for ingress and egress to and from, and for maintenance or repair of, the Shared Facilities in the event of an Emergency and the failure or unavailability of the Manager or its representatives to respond timely to such Emergency. Except in the event of an Emergency, the accessing Project Company shall give the other Project Company and the Manager at least forty-eight (48) hours prior notice of its intent to enter upon the Shared Premises (said notice may be by telephone, e- mail, or any other recognized electronic means in addition to any other methods of notice authorized herein). In the event of an Emergency, prior notice is not required, but the Project Company shall give notice of entry onto the Shared Premises as soon as reasonably practicable thereafter. Any Project Company entering on the Shared Premises or accessing the Shared Facilities shall follow all written safety and security procedures adopted by the Project Companies and/or the Manager with respect to the Shared Premises and/or the Shared Facilities or otherwise applicable to the Shared Premises and/or the Shared Facilities under any binding lease, easement, franchise, rights-of-way, or crossing agreement benefitting or burdening such Shared Premises where the terms thereof have been made available to the entering Project Company. Each Project Company acknowledges that each of the agreements set forth on Exhibit G have been made available to it. Notwithstanding the above, if any part of the Shared Premises is also subject to a lease agreement, easement, license, rights-of-way or other similar agreement with a Project

Company for its respective Project, the Project Company may enter upon any of the Shared Premises that is part of such Project Companys rights pursuant to any such lease agreement, easement, license, rights-of-way or other similar agreement without the need to give prior notice or obtain consent as provided in this Section 2.4(a) unless such entry is with respect to the Shared Facilities located thereon and then only to the extent set forth above.
(b) By Manager. The Manager shall have access to the Shared Premises and Shared Facilities at any time for purposes of complying with its obligations set forth in this Agreement, including (i) inspection of such Shared Premises and the Shared Facilities located thereon, without unduly interfering with the normal operations of the Project Companies and otherwise subject to the terms and conditions set forth in this Agreement, (ii) construction or Operation and Maintenance of the Shared Facilities in accordance with the terms hereof, or (iii) for ingress and egress to and from, and for maintenance or repair of, the Shared Facilities. The Manager shall follow all written safety and security procedures adopted by the Project Companies with respect to the Shared Premises or otherwise applicable to the Shared Premises under any binding lease, easement, franchise, rights-of-way or crossing agreement benefitting or burdening such Shared Premises where the terms thereof have been made available to the Manager by notice pursuant to Section 14.1 hereof.
(c) By Secured Parties. A Secured Party of a Project Company shall have the right to enter onto the Shared Premises for the purposes described in Section 2.4(a)(i) and, in connection with or following the exercise of remedies by the Secured Party under its Security Documents, for the other purposes described in Section 2.4(a), in each case upon five (5) Business Days advance written notice of its entry delivered to the Manager and the other Project Company; provided that such right of entry shall be limited to normal business hours except in the case of an Emergency. Any Secured Party so entering on the Shared Premises or accessing the Shared Facilities shall (i) follow all written safety and security procedures and other site regulations of the Project Companies and/or the Manager with respect to the Shared Premises and/or the Shared Facilities or otherwise applicable to the Shared Premises and/or the Shared Facilities under any binding lease, easement, franchise, rights-of-way or crossing agreement benefitting or burdening such Shared Premises where the terms thereof have been made available to the Project Company that is a debtor of such entering Secured Party, and (ii) not unduly interfere with the normal operations of the Project Companies and the Manager thereon.
2.5 No Interference. Each Project Companys use of the Shared Premises and the Shared Facilities shall comply with the terms of the Shared Premises Property Rights and shall not interfere with the use and enjoyment by the other Project Company of its rights in such Shared Premises or Shared Facilities, subject to all the terms and provisions of this Agreement. Each of the Project Companies shall cooperate in good faith to accommodate the other Project Companys use of the Shared Premises and the Shared Facilities for the benefit of the other Project Companys Project. Subject to the first sentence of this Section 2.5, the use of the Shared Premises and the Shared Facilities by the Project Companies pursuant to and in accordance with the terms of this Agreement will not, separately or in the aggregate, be deemed to constitute an overburdening of the Shared Premises or the Shared Facilities or any portion of either of them.

2.6 Construction of Shared Facilities.
(a) Construction of Shared Facilities. Papago BESS in its role as Manager hereunder shall procure, install and construct the Shared Facilities (including providing or arranging for applicable credit support) on behalf of, and as agent of, the Project Companies pursuant to the EPC Contract and shall, immediately upon the passage of title to the Shared Facilities (including any spare parts relating to the Shared Facilities), assign and convey, and does hereby assign and convey, title to the Shared Facilities (and any associated rights under the EPC Contract, including applicable warranty rights in and to such Shared Facilities) to the Project Companies, as tenants in common in proportion to their respective Proportionate Shares, to be held pursuant to this Agreement.
(b) Construction under EPC Contract. The Shared Facilities shall be constructed pursuant to design and construction plans and specifications set forth in the EPC Contract, which EPC Contract is hereby deemed approved by the Project Companies; provided that any material amendments or modifications to the EPC Contract shall be subject to prior review and approval of the Project Companies (not to be unreasonably withheld, conditioned or delayed). Manager shall diligently commence and complete construction of the Shared Facilities in accordance with the EPC Contract, applicable Governmental Requirements and Good Utility Practice. Manager shall use commercially reasonable efforts to have the Project Companies and the Manager identified as beneficiaries of the warranties and indemnities obtained with respect to the Shared Facilities. The Project Companies and Manager shall coordinate construction of the Projects and the Shared Facilities to minimize disruption to their respective construction activities and schedules and to ensure continued access in and to the Shared Properties as necessary.
(c) Payment of Shared Facilities Construction Costs. Each Project Company shall be responsible for its Proportionate Share of the Shared Facilities Construction Costs. Each Project Company shall reimburse Manager for its Proportionate Share of the Shared Facilities Construction Costs incurred by Manager prior to commencement of construction under the EPC Contract, and shall thereafter either pay directly to the applicable Contractor its Proportionate Share of Shared Facilities Construction Costs as and when due pursuant to the EPC Contract, or reimburse Manager for its Proportionate Share thereof within thirty (30) days of being invoiced therefor, as directed by Manager. Amounts (including amounts determined to be due after resolution of a Dispute) that are not paid as and when due shall accrue interest at the Default Interest Rate until paid. In the event of any dispute regarding the allocation and reimbursement of the Shared Facilities Construction Costs between the Parties which cannot be resolved within sixty (60) days after reasonably diligent good faith efforts, any Party may seek arbitration of the Dispute pursuant to the provisions of Article 13 below. Notwithstanding the foregoing, in no event shall any dispute regarding allocation of costs require the Manager to delay or suspend construction of any Shared Facilities.
(d) Monitoring and Step-In Rights.
(i) The Project Companies shall have the right, each at its sole cost and expense, to monitor the construction of the Shared Facilities, and Manager shall afford reasonable access to the Project Companies for such purpose. Any Project Company exercising such monitoring right shall not interfere with the construction activities of
5 AmericasActive:19632294.7
Manager or any Contractor and shall comply with all of Managers and Contractors workplace safety and security requirements.
(ii) If any default by Manager has occurred and is continuing under the EPC Contract or the O&M Agreement, and Manager has not cured such default within ten (10) days after its occurrence, in the case of a default that can be cured by the payment of money, or thirty (30) days after its occurrence, in the case of a default that cannot be cured solely by the payment of money, any Project Company may, upon two (2) days notice to Manager and the other Project Companies, cure such default on behalf of Manager and take such other actions as may be reasonably necessary to preserve the Parties rights under the EPC Contract or the O&M Agreement, as applicable. The other Project Company shall reimburse the Project Company exercising such rights for its Proportionate Share of all costs and expenses reasonably incurred by such Project Company in exercising such rights and curing such default; provided, however, that such reimbursement shall not release Manager from any obligations or liabilities it might have hereunder in connection with such default under the EPC Contract or O&M Agreement, as applicable.

This LGIA CO-TENANCY AGREEMENT (this Agreement) is made and entered into as of May 7, 2024 (the Effective Date), by and among RE Papago LLC (Papago BESS or Manager) and RE Papago PV LLC (Papago PV), each individually a Co-Tenant and collectively the Co-Tenants), each a Delaware limited liability company. Each of the Co-Tenants and the Manager may also sometimes be referred to in this Agreement as a Party and collectively as the Parties.
RECITALS
A. Papago BESS is developing and will construct, own and operate a battery energy storage project with a maximum installed capacity of 300 MW at the point of interconnection located in Maricopa County, Arizona in the location shown on Exhibit A-1 attached hereto.
B. Papago PV is developing and will construct, own and operate a solar energy generation project with a maximum installed capacity of 150 MW at the point of interconnection located in Maricopa County, Arizona in the location shown on Exhibit A-2 attached hereto .
C. Each Co-Tenant will construct, own and operate its own separate project (Project), including photovoltaic panels, battery energy storage facilities, current inverters and other assets, but will jointly own and share, the rights and obligations under the LGIA (as defined below), as tenants in common.
C. Each Co-Tenant will have beneficial interests in and rights to use certain interconnection and related facilities (the Shared Facilities).
D. Papago BESS is a party to that certain Large Generator Interconnection Agreement by and among Papago BESS, Arizona Public Service Company (APS) and the Central Arizona Water Conservation District (the CAWCD), dated as of December 23, 2019 together with all agreements, schedules, appendices, exhibits and other documents ancillary thereto (as amended or supplemented from time to time, the LGIA) for the purpose of securing interconnection rights for each of the Projects.
D. Papago BESS and Papago PV intend to amend the LGIA to add Papago PV as a party and make certain related changes to the LGIA.
The Parties desire to enter into this Agreement to set forth the terms and conditions under which the Co-Tenants will be co-tenants under the LGIA and share the LGIA among the Co-Tenants and Projects, and the Manager will act as the Co-Tenants manager to administer and manage the Co-Tenants rights and obligations under the LGIA with respect to APS, and certain other related matters.

ARTICLE II CO-TENANCY RIGHTS AND OBLIGATIONS
2.1 Declaration of Intention. The Parties hereby declare that their relationship in and to the LGIA and the Interconnection Customers rights and obligations thereunder is and will be that of tenants-in-common, and that each Co-Tenant will have an undivided interest (Undivided Interest) in the LGIA and the Interconnection Customers rights and obligations thereunder, expressly subject, however, to the terms, conditions, limitations and requirements set forth in this Agreement. Nothing contained in this Agreement will be deemed to constitute the Parties as partners or joint venturers.
2.2 Use of LGIA. The LGIA shall be held and used solely to permit the interconnection of the Projects to the Transmission System and to deliver electricity generated by the respective Projects owned by each Co-Tenant (or by such Co-Tenants successors or permitted assigns) at the Point of Interconnection without discriminating against any Co-Tenant. No Co-Tenant may use or permit the use of the LGIA in a manner that would reasonably be expected to interfere with the use and enjoyment by the other Co-Tenant of such Co-Tenants Project, or to violate Applicable Laws and Regulations; provided that a Co-Tenants non-discriminatory use of the LGIA in compliance with this Agreement shall be deemed to not interfere with any other Co-Tenants use and enjoyment of its Project. In the event of a conflict between the terms of this Agreement and the terms of the LGIA, the requirements under the LGIA shall prevail.
2.3 Installed Capacity. No Co-Tenant shall deliver energy into the Transmission System for its respective Project to the Point of Interconnection to the extent the installed capacity of such Project exceeds its Installed Capacity, or to the extent such delivery of energy is less than the Projects Installed Capacity, otherwise causes the Co-Tenants to collectively exceed the Maximum Capacity. To the extent that conditions exist which result in a Co-Tenant delivering energy to the Point of Interconnection from its respective Project in excess of the Installed Capacity in respect of such Project or otherwise causes the Co-Tenant to collectively exceed the Maximum Capacity, then such Co-Tenant shall at its expense immediately curtail the operation of its Project so as not to exceed its Installed Capacity, or the Maximum Capacity, as applicable.

(a) The Manager may, in accordance with this Section 2.4, direct the Co- Tenants to interrupt or reduce deliveries of electrical power (i) with the prior consent of the Required Co-Tenants, when necessary in order to maintain, repair, replace, remove, investigate, inspect or test any part of any Project; (ii) if the Manager determines, in its reasonable discretion, that interruption or reduction is necessary due to an Emergency Condition; (iii) at the direction of the Transmission Provider pursuant to rights under the LGIA, or (iv) at the direction of APS pursuant to the Tariff. Manager will use commercially reasonable efforts to give the Co-Tenants as much advance notice as is reasonably possible for interruptions, reductions or curtailments under clauses (ii) and (iii).
(b) With respect to any interruption or reduction of deliveries of electrical power pursuant to clauses (i) or (ii) of Section 2.4(a), the Manager shall limit the length of any such interruption or curtailment to the minimum extent and minimum time strictly necessary to correct the problem. Any interruption or curtailment made pursuant to clause (i) of Section 2.4(a) shall be made to the extent commercially reasonable during periods of low or no solar generation or low energy prices.
(c) In the event of any curtailment of interconnection services at the direction the Transmission Provider, such curtailment shall be allocated in the following manner until such curtailment is achieved:
(i) first, each Co-Tenant (if any) that is delivering energy in excess of such Co-Tenants Installed Capacity shall reduce deliveries down to such Co-Tenants Installed Capacity,
(ii) second, to each Co-Tenant in accordance with Section 2.4(d)(ii);
(iii) third, each Co-Tenant shall reduce its energy deliveries so that they do not exceed an amount (the Curtailed Output Cap) equal to (X) such Co-Tenants Installed Capacity, minus (Y) the product of (1) the aggregate number of MW then required for the Project to curtail (after application of preceding clause (i)) times (2) such Co-Tenants Percentage Interest; provided that if during any relevant period of curtailment any Co-Tenant is delivering energy at a level less than its Curtailed Output Cap (any such amount, a Shortfall) either because such Co- Tenants Project is undergoing maintenance, has a forced outage, or other circumstance, then for so long as such Shortfall exists, the Manager shall use reasonable efforts to authorize each other Co-Tenant to generate above such Co- Tenants Curtailed Output Cap by allocating among such other Co-Tenants the Shortfall on a pro rata basis in accordance with such other Co-Tenants Percentage Interests.
